# {{PROJECT_NAME}}

This is a slidenerds deck. You are building presentation slides using Next.js and the `@slidenerds/runtime` package.

## Data conventions

The runtime recognizes these HTML attributes:

| Attribute | Purpose |
|-----------|---------|
| `data-slide` | Marks an element as a slide. The runtime tracks these for navigation and the light table. |
| `data-step` | Marks an element for progressive reveal. Hidden until clicked into view, in order. |
| `data-notes` | Speaker notes. Hidden in presentation mode, rendered in the presenter window. |

## Keyboard controls

| Key | Action |
|-----|--------|
| Space / Right arrow | Advance (next step or next slide) |
| Left arrow / Backspace | Go back |
| Double-click | Previous slide |
| P | Open presenter mode |
| L | Open light table |
| F | Fullscreen |
| Escape | Exit fullscreen |

## Brand config

Read `brand.config.ts` before generating any layout or applying any color. Never hardcode hex values. Use CSS custom properties from the brand config.

## File structure

- `app/page.tsx` - Main slide deck
- `app/layout.tsx` - Root layout with SlideRuntime wrapper
- `app/globals.css` - Global styles with CSS custom properties from brand config
- `brand.config.ts` - Brand configuration (colors, fonts, spacing)

## Slide types

When building slides, use these patterns:
- **Title slide**: Large heading, subtitle, full viewport
- **Content slide**: Heading + body content with `data-step` for reveals
- **Big stat**: Single large number with label and context
- **Quote**: Pull quote with attribution
- **Code**: Syntax highlighted code block
- **Two-up**: Side by side content

## Tips

- Each `<section data-slide="">` is one slide
- Use `data-step` on elements for progressive reveal
- Add `data-notes` elements for speaker notes (hidden during presentation)
- Run `npm run dev` for hot reload while editing
- Press P to preview in presenter mode with notes and timer
